  "doc_id": "4022",
  "text": "To study how CAM-1/ROR inhibits Wnt signaling, we investigated the role of CAM-1 in vulval development, a process requiring multiple Wnts. None of the five cam-1 alleles tested (Fig. 1A ) caused induction defects (Table 1) . However, as vulval development requires several redundant Wnts and receptors [CITATION_1] , we looked for genetic interactions between cam-1 and Wnt receptors lin-17/Frizzled [CITATION_2] and lin-18/Ryk [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] , disrupt the CRD (sa692) (Ailion and Thomas, 2003; [CITATION_5] , or disrupt the insertion of the ECD into the membrane (ak37) [CITATION_6] . By contrast, an allele truncating most of the intracellular domain (gm105) [CITATION_7] , and an allele eliminating the kinase domain (ks52) [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] . We detected additional expression in the VPCs in a previously characterized Pcam-1::CAM-1::GFP strain, WF1863 [CITATION_11] ) (see Fig.  3A ). To test whether cam-1 acts in the VPCs, we tried to rescue the lin-17(lf); cam-1(lf) OI phenotype with an integrated VPC-specific CAM-1::GFP transgene driven by the lst-1 promoter [CITATION_12] . Although Plst-1::CAM-1::GFP was expressed in the relevant VPCs (see Fig. 3G ), it failed to rescue the OI phenotype suggesting that CAM-1 is required in other tissues to negatively regulate vulval induction.",
